<h3></h3>
<div class='layout'><p>10 Book</p><p>第10章 典籍</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>HAND-ON-THIGH STORY: …… An occasion cited by Hari Seldon as……first turning point in……search……a method to develop psychohistory. Unfortunately,……published writings give no indication as to what that "story"……and speculations concerning it (there have been many)……futile. It remains……of……many intriguing mysteries concerning Seldons career.</p><p>毛手毛脚的故事：……哈里·谢顿曾经提到，在他找寻心理史学发展方法的过程中，这是第一个转折点。不幸的是，他的正式着作皆未指出它究竟是什么“故事”，各种臆测（为数众多）则全是捕风捉影。有关谢顿生平始终存在着许多有趣的谜，这只是其中之一。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>ENCYCLOPEDIA GALACTICA</p><p>……《银河百科全书》</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Raindrop Forty-Three stared at Seldon, wild-eyed……breathing heavily. </p><p>雨点四十三瞪着谢顿，眼睛张得老大，呼吸则相当沉重。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>I cant stay here,……said.</p><p>“我不能待在这里。”她说。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon looked about.……one is bothering……Even……Brother from whom we……the dainties said nothing about……He seemed to take us as a perfectly normal pair."</p><p>谢顿四下望了望。“没有人会打扰我们。就连那位给我们美食的兄弟也没说我们什么，他似乎把我们当成一对完全普通的夫妻。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Thats because there is nothing unusual about us--when……light is dim, when……keep your voice……so……tribesman accent is less noticeable,……when I seem calm.……now--"……voice……growing hoarse.</p><p>“那是因为我们没有任何不寻常的地方——当时光线黯淡，当时你压低声音使外族口音不太明显，还有当时我还算冷静。可是现在……”她的声音开始变得嘶哑。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"What of now?"</p><p>“现在怎么样？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I am nervous……tense. I am……in a perspiration."</p><p>“我既焦虑又紧张，我在……流汗。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Who is to notice? Relax. Calm down."</p><p>“谁会注意到呢？放轻松，冷静下来。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I cant relax here. I cant calm down while I……be noticed."</p><p>“我在这里无法轻松。当我可能引起注意时，我冷静不下来。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Where……we to……then?"</p><p>“那么，我们要到哪儿去？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"There……little sheds……resting. I have worked here. I know about them."</p><p>“附近有些供人休憩的小屋。我曾在这里工作，所以我知道。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>She……walking rapidly……and Seldon followed. Up a small ramp, which he would……have noticed in……twilight without her, there……a line of doors, well spread apart.</p><p>她快步向前走，谢顿则紧跟在后。他们爬上一个小坡道，若没有她带路，在昏黄的光线下，他不可能会注意到这条小路。在坡道尽头，有一长列互相间隔很远的门。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"The……at……end,"……muttered.……its free."</p><p>“最旁边那间，”她低声道，“如果没人的话。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>It……unoccupied. A small glowing rectangle said……IN……and……door……ajar.</p><p>那间果然是空的。一块发亮的矩形小板映出“无人使用”几个字，而且门只是微掩着。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Raindrop Forty-Three looked about rapidly, motioned Seldon……then stepped inside herself.……closed……door and, as……did……a small ceiling light brightened……interior.</p><p>雨点四十三迅速张望一番，便示意谢顿进去，接着自己也走进来。当她关上门的时候，天花板的一盏小灯随即照亮这间斗室。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon said,……there……way……sign on……door……indicate this shed is in use?"</p><p>谢顿说：“有没有办法让门上号志显示这间小屋有人使用？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"That happened automatically when……door closed……the light went on," said……Sister.</p><p>“门一关上就自动切换，外面的灯已经亮了。”这位姐妹答道。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon could feel……softly circulating with a small sighing sound,……where on Trantor……that ever-present sound……feel……apparent? </p><p>谢顿感觉得到空气在轻柔地循环，还带着一种微弱的风声。然而在川陀，又有哪里听不到、觉不着这种永不止息的微风呢？</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>The room……not large,……it……a……with a firm, efficient mattress,……what were obviously clean sheets. There……a chair……table, a small refrigerator,……something that looked like an enclosed……plate, probably a tiny food-heater.</p><p>这个房间并不大，却摆了一张具有硬实床垫的便床，上面的床单显然相当清洁。此外还有一把椅子、一张桌子、一台小型冰箱，以及一个看来像是“密封热板”的东西，或许是个微型的食物加热器。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Raindrop Forty-Three……down on……chair, sitting stiffly upright, visibly attempting to force herself into relaxation.</p><p>雨点四十三坐到椅子上，将上身挺得笔直，看得出她在企图强迫自己放松。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon, uncertain as to what he ought to……remained standing till……gestured--a……impatiently--for……to……on……cot. He……so.</p><p>谢顿不确定自己该怎么做，只好继续站着。直到她有点不耐烦地做了个手势，他才依照示意坐到便床上。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Raindrop Forty-Three said softly, as though talking to herself,……it is ever known that I have been here with a man--even if only a tribesman--I shall indeed be an outcast."</p><p>雨点四十三轻柔地、仿佛自言自语地说：“万一让人知道我曾和一名男子在这里，即使只是个外族男子，我也注定会被驱逐出境。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon rose quickly. "Then lets……stay here."</p><p>谢顿急忙站起来。“那我们别待在这里。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Sit down. I cant go……when Im in this mood. Youve been asking about religion. What……you after?"</p><p>“坐下，我在这种心情之下绝不能出去。你一直在问有关宗教的事，究竟是在找什么？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>It seemed to Seldon that……had changed completely. Gone……the passivity,……subservience. There……none of……shyness,……backwardness in……presence of a male.……was glaring at……through narrowed eyes.</p><p>谢顿觉得她完全变了一个人，被动与顺从都已经消失无踪。面对一名男性，她也不再害羞，不再畏缩不前。此时，她正眯起双眼，凶狠地瞪着他。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I told you. Knowledge. Im a scholar. It is my profession……my desire to know, I want to understand people in particular, so I want to learn history.……many worlds,……ancient historical records--the truly ancient historical records--have decayed into myths……legends, often becoming part of a……of religious beliefs or of supernaturalism.……if Mycogen does……have a religion, then--"</p><p>“我告诉过你，我在寻求知识。我是一名学者，追求知识是我的专业和欲望。我尤其想要了解人类，所以我想学习历史。因为在许多世界上，古代的历史记录——真正的古代历史记录，都已经变质为神话和传说，常常成了宗教信仰或超自然论的一部分。但麦曲生如果没有宗教，那么……”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"I said we have history."</p><p>“我说过我们有历史！”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon said, "Twice youve said……have history.……old?"</p><p>谢顿道：“你已经说了两遍。你们的历史有多古老呢？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"It goes back twenty thousand years."</p><p>“上溯两万年前。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"Truly?……us speak frankly. Is it real history or is it something that……degenerated into legend?"</p><p>“真的吗？让我们坦白说吧，它究竟是真实的历史，还是已经退化成传说的那种东西？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"It is real history, of course."</p><p>“当然是真实的历史。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>Seldon……on……point of asking……she could tell,……thought better of……Was there really a chance that history might reach back twenty thousand years……be authentic? He……not a historian himself, so he would have to check with Dors.</p><p>谢顿正想问她如何能判断，却在最后关头打消这个念头。历史真有可能上溯两万年，而仍旧真实可信吗？他自己不是历史学家，所以必须去问问铎丝。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>But it seemed so likely to……that on every world……earliest histories were medleys of self-serving heroisms……minidramas that were meant as morality plays……were……to be taken literally. It……surely true of Helicon,……you would find scarcely a Heliconian……would……swear by……the tales told……insist it……all true history. They would support, as such, even that perfectly ridiculous tale of……first exploration of Helicon……the encounters with large……dangerous flying reptiles--even though nothing like flying reptiles……been found to be native to……world explored……settled by human beings.</p><p>可是他有一种强烈的感觉，那就是在每个世界上，最早期的历史都是一堆大杂烩，充满说教式的英雄事迹与迷你剧本，仅能视为一种道德剧，不能太过当真。赫利肯的情形当然如此，你却很难找到一个不深信那些传说、不坚持它们全是真实历史的赫利肯人。他们就连完全荒诞的故事也照样支持不误，例如人类首次探勘赫利肯时，遇到了危险的巨型飞行爬虫——虽然在人类曾经探勘与殖民的所有世界上，都从未发现任何土生土长的、类似飞行爬虫的动物。</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>He said instead, "How does this history begin?"</p><p>不过他只是问：“这个历史是如何开始的？”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>There……a faraway look in……Sisters eyes, a look that……not focus on Seldon or on anything in……room.……said,……begins with a world--our world.……world."</p><p>这位姐妹的目光显得恍惚，并未聚焦在谢顿或屋内任何一样东西上。她说：“它开始于某个世界——我们的世界，独一的世界。”</p></div>
<div class='layout'><p>"One world?" (Seldon remembered that Hummin……spoken of legends of a single, original world of humanity.)</p><p>“独一的世界？”谢顿想起夫铭提到过有关人类起源于单一世界的传说。</p></div>
